	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Changing concerns, changing objectives</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 November 2001
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>
According to EU Agriculture Commissioner Fischler, in recent years the &quot;common agricultural policy has been subject to the most substantial reforms since its existence&quot;. The EU has &quot;shifted support away from production to new measures such as environmental protection and maintenance of traditional landscapes&quot; and reform has made EU policy &quot;more competitive and less trade distorting . . . In 1991, we used 91% of our budget on export refunds and intervention, thus causing trade distortion and huge stocks. Now that we have opted out of this production race, only 21% will be spent on market support after the full implementation of the reform by 2006. Instead 68% of the budget will be used for direct payments to farmers&quot;. <br />
 In addition the EU has introduced a second pillar to the CAP namely the programmes of support to rural development, which currently account for around 10% of CAP expenditures but which are set to increase considerably. Nominally these new rural development instruments are &quot;not trade distorting at all&quot;.<br /> Alongside the reform of instruments, the objectives of the EU's agricultural policy have also been redefined. In the past, food production was the simple priority. Now food production must be competitive and agriculture is required to fulfill a multiplicity of functions. It must protect the environment, ensure safe and high quality food, maintain traditional landscapes and sustain dynamic rural economies. It is towards providing remuneration to farmers for carrying out these other vital functions to which EU financial assistance to the agricultural sector is now being directed. According to Commissioner Fischler, it cannot be expected that these wider legitimate concerns should be sacrificed on the altar of free trade. According to Commissioner Fischler, whilst respecting the rights of democratic societies to create their own agricultural policies, the main task of international agricultural policy negotiations should be to &quot;find ways to limit the trade-distorting effects of our policies&quot;. </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>

<a href="http://europa.eu.int/rapid/start/cgi/guesten.ksh?p_action.gettxt=gt&amp;doc=SPEECH/01/478|0|RAPID&amp;lg=EN" target="_self">Speech Commissioner Fischler, Cernobbio 19th October 2001 &quot;Feeling...</a> <br /> 
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/rapid/start/cgi/guesten.ksh?p_action.gettxt=gt&amp;doc=SPEECH/01/477|0|RAPID&amp;lg=EN" target="_self">Address Commissioner Fischler on Changing Concerns, Changing Objectives,...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>
While the reforms introduced under the CAP may be judged less trade distorting, the reality is that the reformed CAP is enabling EU agricultural and processed agricultural exporters to win new international markets, including some which are served by ACP producers. When the EU talks of CAP reform and how it has removed the grain mountains the impression is created that policy reform has contained and limited production. This is far from the case. The reform process, by lowering prices, has stimulated domestic consumption of cereals and lowered the costs of surplus disposal. The period of cereal sector reform in the EU has seen EU cereal consumption rise 32.3% and EU production rise 25.7%. Since a low of 24,526 tonnes in the 1995/96 season, EU cereal exports have risen back to around pre-reform levels (36,800 tonnes in 1999/2000 compared to 36,997 tonnes in 1992/93). In the coming years, with EU intervention prices falling below world market prices for major cereals, EU exports are likely to increase beyond the pre-reform levels.<br />
 As the EU Agriculture Commissioner has suggested, EU farmers are indeed responding more to market signals, but these are market signals distorted by the various systems of direct aid payments made available in pursuit of other EU agricultural policy objectives. Normally 50% lower prices would be expected to lead to a contraction in production. However increased levels of direct aid payments have led to a 25% increase in EU cereals production. In the poultry sector &quot;market signals&quot;, in the form of a 50% decline in cereal prices, have massively reduced animal feed costs (which formerly accounted for 70% of total production costs) and allowed a large scale expansion of poultry meat exports whilst at the same time allowing a reduction in the level of export refunds provided.<br /> With CAP distortions becoming less transparent, ACP governments will need to adopt a very careful and sophisticated approach to the debate around CAP reform and EU positions on international rules on agricultural support in the WTO. Unless great care is taken, ACP governments could see more price competitive EU agricultural and processed agricultural product exports taking over a range of markets previously served by ACP producers.</p>
		</div>
		
